edicted, not experimentally validated\", \"Add hydrothermal HCHO source for better environmental flow\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_017\": 0.60,\n        \"rxn_018\": 0.50,\n        \"rxn_019\": 0.72\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.58,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.65,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.85,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.60,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.62,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway has the best environmental progression (Hydrothermal\u2192Surface\u2192Biochemical) but suffers from significant chemical feasibility issues. rxn_017 (CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate) is a massive oversimplification of what would be a multi-step process; direct C3 synthesis from CO\u2082 in one step on greigite is not well-established experimentally at useful yields. rxn_018 (pyruvate \u2192 hydroxypyruvate by simple hydroxylation with water) lacks a clear mechanism \u2014 this would require an oxidant and specific conditions. rxn_019 (reductive amination) requires a reductant not specified in the reaction.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_017\", \"rxn_018\", \"rxn_019\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Break rxn_017 into multiple steps (CO\u2082 \u2192 acetyl-CoA analog \u2192 pyruvate)\", \"Specify oxidant for pyruvate hydroxylation in rxn_018\", \"Specify reducing agent (e.g., Fe\u00b2\u207a, H\u2082S) for reductive amination in rxn_019\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.85,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0.82,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.88,\n        \"rxn_013\": 0.68\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.80,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.75,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.72,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.76,\n      \"feedback\": \"This hybrid pathway combines cyanosulfidic HCN photoreduction with the formaldimine route from Li et al. 2024. The early steps are well-supported but the final coupling step (rxn_013) retains the high energy barrier issue. The integration of cyanosulfidic chemistry with computational formaldimine pathways is creative and reflects the literature's suggestion that formaldimine may be more important than previously recognized.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"],\n      \"suggestions\": [\"Same as P8: address the 55.5 kcal/mol barrier\", \"Consider alternative final step via Strecker on glycolaldehyde\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.86,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"This is an excellent synthesis network for prebiotic serine production. The network demonstrates strong alignment with the literature, incorporating the cyanosulfidic network (Ritson & Sutherland 2012, 2023), Strecker synthesis, the computational formaldimine route (Li et al. 2024), formamide chemistry, and the non-enzymatic serine shunt. The network topology is well-designed with 20 molecules, 19 reactions, and 5 hub molecules providing good connectivity. Formaldehyde (mol_008) serves as the central hub with very high connectivity, which accurately reflects its central role in prebiotic C1 chemistry.\\n\\nStrengths: (1) Multiple independent pathways to serine providing chemical redundancy; (2) Strong literature citations and alignment with Patel et al. 2015, Ritson & Sutherland 2012/2023, Li et al. 2024, and Parker et al. 2011; (3) Good environmental flow from hydrothermal to surface to biochemical; (4) Hub molecules are well-chosen and reflect actual prebiotic chemistry.\\n\\nWeaknesses: (1) Some reactions are oversimplified (rxn_009, rxn_017); (2) The pyruvate pathway (P9) has significant feasibility issues; (3) The formaldimine coupling step (rxn_013) has a very high barrier; (4) Some surface reactions lack mineral catalyst specifications; (5) Glyceraldehyde (mol_010) is listed 