d be made explicit. The downstream Strecker chain (rxn_004\u2192007) is well-supported.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_015\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Revise rxn_015 to reflect actual formamide thermolysis products (HCN + H\u2082O, or CO + NH\u2083)\", \"If HCHO is needed, route through a separate photoreduction step\", \"Consider citing Saladino et al. for formamide-based prebiotic syntheses\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_003\": 0.90,\n                \"rxn_004\": 0.85,\n                \"rxn_020\": 0.73\n            },\n            \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.78,\n            \"pathway_coherence\": 0.75,\n            \"environmental_progression\": 0.72,\n            \"target_achievement\": 0.75,\n            \"overall_confidence\": 0.75,\n            \"feedback\": \"The aldol-amination one-pot route is inspired by meteoritic chemistry (Koga & Naraoka 2017), where hydroxy amino acids likely formed from aldehydes and ammonia on parent bodies. rxn_020 combining glycolaldehyde + HCHO + NH\u2083 in a single pot is plausible but the mechanism is not fully specified \u2014 does it proceed through an aldol to give glyceraldehyde then amination, or through a direct multi-component coupling? The yield and selectivity for serine vs. isoserine or other isomers should be addressed.\",\n            \"approved\": false,\n            \"problematic_reactions\": [\"rxn_020\"],\n            \"suggestions\": [\"Clarify the mechanism of rxn_020: sequential aldol + amination vs. concerted\", \"Address selectivity for serine vs. isoserine and other C3 HAAs\", \"Specify temperature and pH conditions matching meteorite parent body alteration\"]\n        },\n        {\n            \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n            \"reaction_scores\": {\n                \"rxn_016\": 0.88,\n                \"rxn_017\": 0.78,\n                \"rxn_018\":